This section details how Fourier optics propagation (Fig. 3 step 2: AS) is performed in this paper. Analysis using the Fourier transform formalism is a powerful optical modeling tool introduced and widely popularized by Goodman.11 It provides a straightforward method for evaluating, in any point in space, the properties (phase and amplitude) of a monochromatic electromagnetic wave, propagating in a free-space medium (linear, homogeneous, non-magnetic, free of electric charge and current). More specifically, the accurate angular spectrum (AS) method is used in this paper for optical wave propagation. A complex field phasor U(x, y; z) can be expressed at any propagation plane z along the optical axis, as long as the initial phasor U(x, y; 0) is known:U(x, y; z) = F −1{F{U(x, y; 0)}Hz(fx, fy)} Hz(fx, fy) = F{hz(x, y)} = exp [ i2πz √ λ−2 − f2x − f2y
] (8) where (fx, fy) are the spatial frequencies of the field, Hz is the transfer function of the wave propagation phenomenon, and hz is the impulse response of the system. Note that since the angular spectrum method is constrained by free-space assumptions, it cannot be employed to compute the optical field propagation through an MLDOE. Therefore, Fourier optics is bounded to propagate a complex field, calculated after the MLDOE, onto a target plane.
